revision.text:
The following is a list of common non-native [[pronounce|pronunciations]] that [[English language|English]] speakers make when trying to speak foreign languages. Many of these are due to transfer of [[phonology|phonological]] rules from English to the new language as well as differences in [[grammar]] and [[syntax]] that they encounter.

This article uses [[International Phonetic Alphabet]] pronunciation. See [[Help:IPA pronunciation key]] and [[IPA chart for English]] for an introduction.

== Esperanto ==
{{See also|Esperanto phonology}}
*While English speakers tend to assimilate {{IPA|/m/}} to {{IPA|[ɱ]}} before {{IPA|/f/}} or {{IPA|/v/}}, as well {{IPA|/n/}} to {{IPA|[ŋ]}} before {{IPA|/k/}} or {{IPA|/ɡ/}}, neither of which occurs in "strictly regular" Esperanto.{{sfnp|Blanke|2001|pp=41, 330–331}} However, since Zamenhof himself recognized [[Esperanto phonology#Assimilation|this type of assimilation]], there is debate over whether this is actually an error.
*Speakers tend to pronounce Esperanto {{IPA|/ɛ/}} as {{IPA|[eɪ]}}, the vowel of ''pay''.{{sfnp|Blanke|2001|p=37}}
*Speakers tend to reduce unstressed vowels.{{sfnp|Blanke|2001|p=38}}
*Speakers tend to pronounce {{IPA|/x/}} as {{IPA|[k]}} or otherwise have a hard time pronouncing it.  This sort of difficulty is behind the gradual shift from {{angbr|ĥ}} to {{angbr|k}} (see [[Esperanto phonology#Loss of phonemic ĥ]]).{{sfnp|Blanke|2001|p=39}}
*Speakers tend to pronounce the [[rhotic consonant]] as {{IPA|[ɹ]}}, rather than an [[alveolar trill]].  Speakers of [[rhotic and non-rhotic accents|non-rhotic]] accents tend to mute the r when at end of a word or before consonant.{{sfnp|Blanke|2001|p=40}}
*Other pronunciation difficulties are related to spelling pronunciations of digraphs. The digraph {{angbr|sc}} represents {{IPA|/st͡s/}}, though speakers may substitute {{IPA|[s]}} or {{IPA|[sk]}}. The digraph {{angbr|kn}} represents {{IPA|/kn/}}, though speakers may mute the {{IPA|/k/}}. The {{angbr|g}} in the digraph {{angbr|ng}} is always pronounced.{{sfnp|Blanke|2001|p=41}}

== German ==
{{See also|Standard German phonology}}
* There are several German vowels that create problems for English speakers:
** One of the most difficult is German {{IPA|/eː/}} as it is further forward in the mouth than in varieties of Standard English so that speakers may pronounce German ''Geht'' as if it were English ''gate''.{{sfnp|Hall|2003|p=81}}
** Similarly, speakers may pronounce German {{IPA|/oː/}} with the vowel of ''goat'' so that ''ohne'' is pronounced {{IPA|[ˈəʊnə]}}.{{sfnp|Hall|2003|p=91}}
** English speakers tend to have difficulty with the front rounded vowels, {{IPA|/øː/}}, {{IPA|/œ/}}, {{IPA|/yː/}}, and {{IPA|/ʏ/}}{{sfnp|Hall|2003|pp=92-97}} (written {{angbr|ö}} and {{angbr|ü}}).
** Speakers have some difficulty with German {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/aː/}}, which may be pronounced as {{IPA|[æ]}} and {{IPA|[ɑː]}}, respectively.{{sfnp|Hall|2003|pp=85-87}} 
* English speakers also have difficulty with the two sounds represented by ''ch'' ({{IPA|[x]}} and {{IPA|[ç]}}) in German, particularly the latter.{{sfnp|Hall|2003|p=46}} Often both are replaced with {{IPA|[k]}}; replacement of {{IPA|[ç]}} with {{IPA|[ʃ]}} is also common. They also have difficulty with the [[guttural r]] of most German dialects.<ref>http://joycep.myweb.port.ac.uk/pronounce/consonch.html</ref>{{better source|date=December 2012}}

== Mandarin Chinese ==
{{see also|Standard Chinese phonology}}
*English speakers have difficulty with the 4 lexical [[Tone (linguistics)|tones]] of [[Mandarin Chinese]].{{sfnp|Gottfried|Suiter|1997}}

== Russian ==
{{See also|Russian phonology}}
* Some speakers have difficulty with the trilled {{IPA|[r]}} in Russian, especially the palatalized {{IPA|[rʲ]}} since neither are sounds of English.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=185}}
** Non-rhotic speakers, even after learning the rolled-r, are prone to omit {{IPA|/r/}} in such Russian words as удар {{IPA|[ʊˈdar]}} ('blow') and горка {{IPA|[ˈɡorkə]}} ('hillock').
* Depending on the speaker's dialect, they may have difficulty with "dark l" {{IPA|[ɫ]}} (that is, velarized {{IPA|[l]}}, which in Russian contrasts with a palatalized {{IPA|[lʲ]}}) in positions other than in the syllable coda.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=168}}
* Difficulty with Russian vowels:
** Most English speakers have no {{IPA|[ɨ]}} (although it is an allophone in some dialects, see [[weak vowel merger]]) and speakers generally have difficulty producing the sound.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=33}} They may instead produce {{IPA|[ɪ]}}.
** Speakers may replace {{IPA|/e/}} with the diphthong in ''day''.  e.g. {{IPA|[ˈdeɪlə]}} instead of {{IPA|[ˈdʲelə]}} дело ('affair').{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=41}}
** Speakers are likely to diphthongize {{IPA|/u/}}, making сижу {{IPA|[sʲɪˈʐu]}}  ('I sit') sound more like {{IPA|[sɪˈʒʊu]}}.  Some speakers may also universally front it to {{IPA|[ʉ]}}.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=64}}
** Speakers may also diphthongize {{IPA|/i/}} in a similar fashion, especially in open syllables.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=30}}
** Speakers may have difficulty with Russian {{IPA|/o/}}, pronouncing it as either {{IPA|[ɔ]}} or {{IPA|[oʊ]}}.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=56}}
** It is likely that speakers will make the second element of Russian diphthongs insufficiently close, making them resemble English diphthongs (e.g., {{IPA|[druzʲeɪ]}} instead of {{IPA|[druzʲej]}}) or pronounce it too long.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=75}}
** Speakers may pronounce {{IPA|/a/}} as {{IPA|[æ]}} in closed syllables так ('so') and {{IPA|[ɑ]}} in open syllables два ('two').{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=47}}
* Speakers may also have difficulty with the [[Russian vowel reduction]] system as well as other allophonic vowels.
** Tendency to reverse the distribution of {{IPA|[ɐ]}} and {{IPA|[ə]}}. English speakers tend to pronounce {{IPA|[ə]}} in the pretonic position, right where {{IPA|[ɐ]}} is required in Russian, while they pronounce {{IPA|[ɐ]}} in pre-pretonic positions, where {{IPA|[ə]}} occurs. Thus, speakers may say  голова ('head') as {{IPA|[ɡɐləˈva]}} instead of {{IPA|[ɡəlɐˈva]}} and сторона ('side') as {{IPA|[stɐrəˈna]}} instead of {{IPA|[stərɐˈna]}}.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=55}}
* There are no cues to indicate correct stress in Russian. Speakers must memorize where primary and secondary stress resides in each word and are likely to make mistakes.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=212}}
* Speakers tend to fail to geminate double consonants.{{sfnp|Jones|Ward|1969|p=214}}

== Serbo-Croatian ==
{{See also|Serbo-Croatian phonology}}
* Speakers may have a difficulty with Serbo-Croatian pitch accent and vowel length. This rarely leads to loss of intelligibility as long as the word stress is correct.{{sfnp|Kordić|1997|p=8}}{{sfnp|Alexander|2006|p=4}}
** Speakers may transfer vowel length from English, producing longer vowels before voiced consonants (such as {{IPA|/b/}} or {{IPA|/z/}}) and shorter vowels before the voiceless ones (such as {{IPA|/p/}} or {{IPA|/s/}}) - see [[pre-fortis clipping]]. In Serbo-Croatian, vowels can be long or short in any environment; in fact, there are minimal pairs based only on length: compare ''grad'' {{nowrap|{{IPA|/ɡrâd/}}}} ('city') with ''grad'' {{IPA|/ɡrâːd/}} ('hall').{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=10}}
** If speakers learn to produce correct vowel length, they may diphthongize long {{IPA|/iː, uː, eː, oː/}} to {{IPA|[ɪi, ʊu, eɪ, oʊ]}} instead of the correct {{IPA|[{{IPA link|iː}}, {{IPA link|uː}}, {{IPA link|e̞|eː}}, {{IPA link|o̞|oː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Alexander|2006|p=3}}{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|pp=12, 20}}
* Speakers may incorrectly reduce unstressed vowels to {{IPAblink|ə}}, yielding pronunciations such as {{IPA|[ləpǒtə]}} instead of {{IPA|[lepǒta]}} for ''lepota'' ('beauty'). In Serbo-Croatian, vowels do not change their quality in unstressed positions.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=10}}{{sfnp|Kordić|1997|p=4}}
* Voiced consonants ({{IPA|/b, d, ɡ, dʒ, dʑ, z, ʒ/}}) can be only partially {{IPA|[b̥, d̥, ɡ̊, d̥ʒ̊, d̥ʑ̊, z̥, ʒ̊]}} rather than fully voiced {{IPA|[{{IPA link|b}}, {{IPA link|d̪|d}}, {{IPA link|ɡ}}, {{IPA link|dʐ|dʒ}}, {{IPA link|dʑ}}, {{IPA link|z}}, {{IPA link|ʐ|ʒ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|pp=30−31}}
** Similarly, {{IPA|/ʋ/}} (which phonologically is an approximant and therefore not the voiced counterpart of {{IPA|/f/}}) can also be realized as a partially voiced fricative {{IPA|[v̥]}} instead of a fully voiced weak fricative {{IPAblink|v|ʋ̝}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=30}}{{sfnp|Morén|2005|pp=5–6}}
* Speakers may incorrectly realize the voiceless stops {{IPA|/p, t, k/}} as aspirated {{IPA|[pʰ, tʰ, kʰ]}}.{{sfnp|Alexander|2006|p=3}}{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|pp=30−31, 33}}
* Speakers may realize {{IPA|/n, t, d/}} as alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n}}, {{IPA link|t}}, {{IPA link|d}}]}} rather than dental {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n̪}}, {{IPA link|t̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪}}]}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|pp=31, 34}}
** Speakers may incorrectly transfer allophones of English {{IPA|/t/}} to Serbo-Croatian, yielding pronunciations such as {{IPA|[tʃûɾi]}} instead of {{IPA|[tʃûti]}} for ''čuti'' ('to hear') or {{IPA|[ɲûʔn̩]}} instead of {{IPA|[ɲûtn̩]}} for ''njutn'' ('newton'), all of which sound strange to native ears and might not even be understood as belonging to the {{IPA|/t/}} phoneme, potentially leading to a serious loss of intelligibility.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=31}}
* Speakers may have a difficulty distinguishing {{IPA|/tʃ, dʒ/}} from {{IPA|/tɕ, dʑ/}}. This does not lead to loss of intelligibility as many natives merge them as well.{{sfnp|Kordić|1997|p=5}}{{sfnp|Alexander|2006|pp=3−4}}
** Speakers who try to distinguish {{IPA|/tʃ, dʒ/}} from {{IPA|/tɕ, dʑ/}} may realize the former with inappropriate palatalization, i.e. as palato-alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|tʃ}}, {{IPA link|dʒ}}]}} instead of flat postalveolar (laminal retroflex) {{IPA|[{{IPA link|tʂ|t̻ʂ̻}}, {{IPA link|dʐ|d̻ʐ̻}}]}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=32}}
** The same applies to {{IPA|/ʃ, ʒ/}}, which can be realized as {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʃ}}, {{IPA link|ʒ}}]}} instead of {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʂ|ʂ̻}}, {{IPA link|ʐ|ʐ̻}}]}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=32}}
* Speakers may realize {{IPA|/x/}} as glottal {{IPAblink|h}}, rather than a weak velar fricative {{IPAblink|x|x̞}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=33}}
* The palatal sounds {{IPA|/ɲ, ʎ/}} may be realized as sequences {{IPA|[nj, lj]}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=34}}
* Instead of a trill {{IPAblink|r}}, {{IPA|/r/}} can be realized as a postalveolar approximant {{IPAblink|ɹ̠}}.{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|pp=32–33}}
* {{IPA|/j/}} preceded within the same word by a vowel (as in ''gaj'' {{IPA|/ɡâːj/}} ('grove')) can be articulated with an insufficiently raised tongue ({{IPA|[ɪ̯]}} instead of {{IPA|[i̯]}} or {{IPAblink|j}}).{{sfnp|Hodge|Janković|1965|p=29}}

